Containerization is a lightweight alternative to virtualization. Instead of creating full virtual machines. 
Containers package an application and its dependencies together so it runs consistently on any system. 
Containers share the host operating system, making them faster, smaller, and more efficient than VMs.
Example: A container can run a web server, database, or microservice without needing a full OS installation.
A container runtime is the software responsible for creating, starting, and stopping containers.
It takes a container image and turns it into a running container. 
Without a runtime, container images cannot run.

Examples of runtimes:
Docker Engine
containerd
CRI-O

These tools manage the container lifecycle and interact with the operating system.
